li.p:
g does not have a global minimum;
it is unclear
(at this point in our work)
if g increases without bound,
so we can't say for certain whether or not g has a global maximum.

We observe that

  \lim_{x \to \infty} g'(x) =\mathstrut \amp  \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{(x+4)(x-1)^2}{x-2}
  =\mathstrut \amp  \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{x^3 + 2x^2 - 7x + 4}{x-2} \cdot \frac{\frac{1}{x}}{\frac{1}{x}}
  =\mathstrut \amp  \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{x^2 + 2x - 7 + \frac{4}{x}}{1 - \frac{2}{x}}
  =\mathstrut \amp  \infty

Since g'(x) \to \infty as x \to \infty,
this tells us that g increases without bound as x \to \infty.
